{{see|émotion}}

==English==

===Etymology===
From French ''émotion'', from ''émouvoir'' 'excite' based on Latin ''emovere'', from ''e-'' (variant of ''ex-'') 'out' and ''movere'' 'move'.
===Pronunciation===
*{{IPA|/əˈmoʊʃn̩/ (GA), /ɛˈmʌʊʃn̩/ (CanE)}}
*{{Audio|en-ca-emotion.ogg|Audio (CA)}}
*{{audio|en-us-emotion_2.ogg|Audio (US)}}
*:Rhymes: [[Rhymes:English:-əʊʃən|-əʊʃən]]

===Noun===
'''emotion''' ('''emotions''')
#A [[person]]'s internal state of being, normally based in or tied to their internal (physical) and external (social) sensory [[feeling]]s.

===Adjective===
'''emotional'''
#acting illogically, or with much emotion

